    "story": "The Great Robot Kart Challenge<br><br>Morice had been looking forward to Stretford Grammar School\u2019s Technology Day for weeks. His class had been invited to test self-driving go-karts designed by older pupils.<br><br>Ben, however, was interested in only one thing.<br><br>\u201cDo the robots make snacks?\u201d he asked.<br><br>Emily sighed.<br><br>\u201cThey drive karts.\u201d<br><br>\u201cWhat a missed opportunity.\u201d<br><br>\u2e3b<br><br>The visitors gathered in the engineering hall, where a distinguished inventor, Dr Patel, welcomed them.<br><br>\u201cOur robots can recognise corners, avoid obstacles and even park themselves.\u201d<br><br>Ben\u2019s eyes widened.<br><br>\u201cSo\u2026 they can probably do my homework too?\u201d<br><br>\u201cI\u2019m afraid not,\u201d Dr Patel smiled.<br><br>\u2e3b<br><br>The workshop buzzed with excitement. Teams hurried between tables, while teachers tried to keep order.<br><br>\u201cPlease disperse into your assigned groups,\u201d called Mr Green.<br><br>Within moments the noisy crowd spread across the hall.<br><br>\u2e3b<br><br>Each team received a robot kart kit.<br><br>\u201cOur endeavour today,\u201d explained Dr Patel, \u201cis to build a reliable racing machine.\u201d<br><br>Morice immediately embraced the challenge.<br><br>Emily carefully organised the components.<br><br>Oliver read every instruction twice.<br><br>Ben wore the safety goggles upside down.<br><br>\u2e3b<br><br>\u201cWe\u2019ll need an economical design,\u201d Emily said.<br><br>\u201cIf we waste parts now, we won\u2019t have enough later.\u201d<br><br>Ben nodded.<br><br>\u201cI also believe in saving money.\u201d<br><br>\u201cReally?\u201d<br><br>\u201cYes. That\u2019s why I bought these goggles for fifty pence.\u201d<br><br>\u201cThey\u2019re swimming goggles.\u201d<br><br>\u2e3b<br><br>The first task was to **extract** a tiny computer chip from a protective case.<br><br>Morice succeeded immediately.<br><br>Ben tried pulling with such enthusiasm that the chip flew across the table.<br><br>\u201cIt continues to elude me,\u201d he admitted.<br><br>Oliver quietly picked it up from inside Ben\u2019s lunchbox.<br><br>\u2e3b<br><br>As they worked, Dr Patel explained that engineers sometimes faced enormous difficulties.<br><br>\u201cIn places suffering from drought, poor harvests may lead to **famine**. Technology can help farmers grow crops more efficiently.\u201d<br><br>Everyone listened with earnest attention.<br><br>Even Ben stopped joking for nearly thirty seconds.<br><br>\u2e3b<br><br>Outside the workshop stood a small wooden dwelling that had once belonged to the school gardener.<br><br>It was now used as a weather station.<br><br>A new observation tower would soon be erected beside it.<br><br>\u201cOur weather sensors will help us understand changing conditions,\u201d Dr Patel explained.<br><br>\u2e3b<br><br>Back inside, trouble began.<br><br>Ben proudly announced,<br><br>\u201cI\u2019ve improved the design.\u201d<br><br>Everyone looked.<br><br>He had connected two wires that definitely did not belong together.<br><br>A loud beep filled the room.<br><br>The robot spun in circles.<br><br>\u201cWhat happened?\u201d Oliver asked.<br><br>\u201cI may have made one tiny adjustment.\u201d<br><br>Emily looked bewildered.<br><br>\u201cOne?\u201d<br><br>\u2e3b<br><br>The robot charged towards a stack of cardboard boxes.<br><br>Crash!<br><br>Boxes flew everywhere.<br><br>It was hardly a calamity, but it certainly looked dramatic.<br><br>Mr Green rushed over.<br><br>\u201cHas anyone been hurt?\u201d<br><br>\u201cNo,\u201d Morice replied.<br><br>\u201cBut our robot appears very enthusiastic.\u201d<br><br>\u2e3b<br><br>Dr Patel examined the machine.<br><br>\u201cThe damage isn\u2019t **fatal**.\u201d<br><br>He smiled.<br><br>\u201cA good engineer learns from mistakes.\u201d<br><br>Ben looked relieved.<br><br>\u201cI was afraid we\u2019d be expelled before lunch.\u201d<br><br>\u201cOnly if you keep driving into furniture,\u201d Mr Green laughed.<br><br>\u2e3b<br><br>By lunchtime everyone was feeling **fatigue** after hours of building.<br><br>Oliver stretched.<br><br>\u201cMy brain needs a holiday.\u201d<br><br>Ben opened his lunchbox.<br><br>\u201cMy sandwiches look rather bland.\u201d<br><br>Emily raised an eyebrow.<br><br>\u201cThey\u2019re cheese.\u201d<br><br>\u201cI know.\u201d<br><br>\u201cThey\u2019re supposed to taste like cheese.\u201d<br><br>\u2e3b<br><br>After lunch came the obstacle course.<br><br>The robot needed to stop before a painted line marked CAUTION.<br><br>Morice\u2019s team watched nervously.<br><br>The kart rolled forward\u2026<br><br>slowed\u2026<br><br>and stopped perfectly.<br><br>\u201c**Flawless**!\u201d exclaimed Ben.<br><br>Dr Patel nodded.<br><br>\u201cThe programming is excellent.\u201d<br><br>\u2e3b<br><br>Another team\u2019s robot ignored the line completely.<br><br>It bumped gently into a traffic cone.<br><br>The cone wobbled before falling over.<br><br>Its owner tried to **feign** confidence.<br><br>\u201cI meant to test the cone.\u201d<br><br>Nobody believed him.<br><br>\u2e3b<br><br>One boy from another school became rather brazen.<br><br>\u201cOur robot is unbeatable,\u201d he announced loudly.<br><br>Moments later his machine drove backwards into a hedge.<br><br>The spectators burst into laughter.<br><br>Ben whispered,<br><br>\u201cI think confidence should sometimes come with a warning label.\u201d<br><br>\u2e3b<br><br>The final challenge required every team to explain their design.<br><br>Morice spoke clearly.<br><br>Emily described the programming.<br><br>Oliver explained how they had corrected mistakes.<br><br>Ben\u2019s presentation demonstrated remarkable brevity.<br><br>\u201cOur robot works.\u201d<br><br>He sat down.<br><br>Dr Patel smiled.<br><br>\u201cShort and effective.\u201d<br><br>\u2e3b<br><br>During questions, one teacher asked,<br><br>\u201cWhat was your greatest burden today?\u201d<br><br>Emily answered,<br><br>\u201cMaking sure Ben didn\u2019t improve anything else.\u201d<br><br>The hall erupted with laughter.<br><br>\u2e3b<br><br>Mr Green congratulated the class.<br><br>\u201cIt was evident that every team improved throughout the day.\u201d<br><br>Dr Patel agreed.<br><br>\u201cThe best engineers are not those who never make mistakes.\u201d<br><br>\u201cThey are those who learn from them.\u201d<br><br>\u2e3b<br><br>As the pupils packed away their equipment, Ben spotted one final button on the robot.<br><br>\u201cI wonder what this does.\u201d<br><br>\u201cDon\u2019t touch it,\u201d everyone shouted.<br><br>Too late.<br><br>The robot switched on again and drove straight towards the exit.<br><br>Fortunately, its battery finally decided to cease working halfway across the playground.<br><br>It stopped beside a flower bed.<br><br>Ben folded his arms proudly.<br><br>\u201cI was simply testing its long-distance performance.\u201d<br><br>Emily laughed.<br><br>\u201cOf course you were.\u201d<br><br>On the journey home, Morice smiled to himself. They had learned about technology, teamwork and problem-solving, but the funniest lesson of all was that no machine\u2014no matter how clever\u2014could ever be as unpredictable as Ben. Even Dr Patel admitted that while robots could calculate almost everything, they still had no idea how to prepare for one exceptionally boisterous Year 6 pupil.<br><br>",
