    "story": "The Great Park Treasure Hunt<br><br>The Year 6 pupils from Greenfield Primary had been invited to spend a day at Stretford Grammar School. Instead of ordinary lessons, they were taking part in a high-tech treasure hunt in a country park. Their challenge was to solve clues using tablets, drones and teamwork.<br><br>Ben arrived wearing an ostentatious backpack covered in flashing lights and attached a flamboyant orange water bottle to the side.<br><br>Emily stared.<br><br>\u201cAre you going treasure hunting or landing an aeroplane?\u201d<br><br>Ben grinned.<br><br>\u201cI believe in being easy to find.\u201d<br><br>\u201cNobody could lose you,\u201d Oliver laughed.<br><br>\u2e3b<br><br>Mrs Patel, the organiser, welcomed the visitors.<br><br>\u201cIt is a great **privilege** to work with Stretford Grammar pupils today. Before we begin, I must **proclaim** one important rule.\u201d<br><br>Everyone became quiet.<br><br>\u201cI **prohibit** anyone from leaving their team or climbing over fences.\u201d<br><br>Ben nodded seriously.<br><br>\u201cI\u2019ll try my best.\u201d<br><br>Emily whispered,<br><br>\u201cThat sentence worries me.\u201d<br><br>\u2e3b<br><br>Each team received a digital map.<br><br>\u201cOur first task is to **procure** enough information from the clues to unlock the treasure chest,\u201d Mrs Patel explained.<br><br>Morice carefully opened the first envelope.<br><br>Inside was a puzzle asking the teams to extract hidden letters from several words.<br><br>Oliver solved it with painstaking care.<br><br>Emily checked every answer.<br><br>Ben announced,<br><br>\u201cI\u2019ve finished.\u201d<br><br>\u201cYou\u2019ve only written your name,\u201d said Morice.<br><br>\u2e3b<br><br>The map led them towards a **quaint** stone bridge crossing a slow river.<br><br>The water looked wonderfully placid, but Mrs Patel pointed ahead.<br><br>\u201cDon\u2019t be fooled. After heavy rain, the river becomes surprisingly perilous.\u201d<br><br>Ben peered over the side.<br><br>\u201cSo there really is some peril?\u201d<br><br>\u201cThere can be,\u201d she replied, \u201cwhich is why we stay on the path.\u201d<br><br>\u2e3b<br><br>The next clue was hidden beneath a narrow wooden walkway.<br><br>One loose plank looked rather precarious.<br><br>\u201cNo one steps there,\u201d Mrs Patel warned.<br><br>Instead, she handed Ben a litter picker.<br><br>\u201cI\u2019ll oblige you with a safer job.\u201d<br><br>Ben smiled proudly.<br><br>\u201cI\u2019ve finally been promoted.\u201d<br><br>\u2e3b<br><br>Halfway through the course, the pupils discovered a robot ranger beside a bird hide.<br><br>Although its movements were slightly feeble, it could collect rubbish without disturbing wildlife.<br><br>\u201cIt isn\u2019t the fastest robot,\u201d said Morice.<br><br>\u201cBut it does a wonderful job.\u201d<br><br>\u2e3b<br><br>Another clue described a village that had once suffered famine after years of poor harvests. Engineers later built clever irrigation systems, helping it become **prosperous** once again.<br><br>Emily smiled.<br><br>\u201cSo science really can change lives.\u201d<br><br>Mrs Patel nodded.<br><br>\u201cExactly.\u201d<br><br>\u2e3b<br><br>The drone suddenly spotted something shiny beneath a bush.<br><br>Ben rushed forward, only to stop suddenly.<br><br>\u201cI\u2019m perplexed.\u201d<br><br>\u201cWhat is it?\u201d asked Oliver.<br><br>\u201cIt\u2019s just someone\u2019s lost lunchbox.\u201d<br><br>\u2e3b<br><br>Inside the lunchbox was a note:<br><br>Please don\u2019t plunder my biscuits again, Ben.<br><br>The whole group laughed.<br><br>Ben looked innocent.<br><br>\u201cI\u2019ve never seen this box before.\u201d<br><br>Emily raised an eyebrow.<br><br>\u201cReally?\u201d<br><br>Ben decided to feign surprise.<br><br>\u201cWhat an extraordinary coincidence.\u201d<br><br>\u2e3b<br><br>Further along the trail they found an old oak tree.<br><br>A sign explained that many people had shown **prejudice** against bats, believing they were dangerous.<br><br>\u201cIn fact,\u201d Mrs Patel explained, \u201cmost bats are harmless and extremely helpful because they eat insects.\u201d<br><br>\u201cSo the stories weren\u2019t true?\u201d asked Ben.<br><br>\u201cExactly.\u201d<br><br>\u2e3b<br><br>The pupils soon reached the final challenge.<br><br>The clue read:<br><br>Perceive what cannot easily be seen.<br><br>Morice looked carefully around.<br><br>He noticed tiny arrows carved into several stones.<br><br>\u201cI can perceive a pattern!\u201d<br><br>Emily followed the arrows.<br><br>\u201cThey lead towards the hill.\u201d<br><br>\u2e3b<br><br>At the top stood a picnic shelter with a polished wooden table.<br><br>A small metal box was hidden underneath.<br><br>Ben tried to lift the lid.<br><br>Nothing happened.<br><br>Oliver examined the lock with painstaking attention.<br><br>\u201cIt\u2019s a number puzzle.\u201d<br><br>Together they solved it.<br><br>Inside was a golden key.<br><br>\u2e3b<br><br>The key opened a treasure chest containing chocolate medals and certificates.<br><br>Mrs Patel smiled.<br><br>\u201cYou\u2019ve completed every challenge with flawless teamwork.\u201d<br><br>Ben looked delighted.<br><br>\u201cI helped too!\u201d<br><br>\u201cYou certainly did,\u201d laughed Morice.<br><br>\u201cYou kept us entertained.\u201d<br><br>\u2e3b<br><br>As everyone rested, Ben yawned.<br><br>\u201cI\u2019ve got serious fatigue.\u201d<br><br>Emily laughed.<br><br>\u201cYou\u2019ve walked less than everyone else.\u201d<br><br>\u201cI\u2019ve been thinking.\u201d<br><br>\u201cVery loudly.\u201d<br><br>\u2e3b<br><br>Before boarding the coach, Mrs Patel gathered the pupils together.<br><br>\u201cWhat was today\u2019s greatest lesson?\u201d<br><br>Morice answered first.<br><br>\u201cWorking together.\u201d<br><br>Emily said,<br><br>\u201cLooking carefully before making decisions.\u201d<br><br>Oliver added,<br><br>\u201cChecking every clue.\u201d<br><br>Ben thought for a moment.<br><br>\u201cI\u2019ve learned not to **provoke** hungry geese.\u201d<br><br>Everyone looked confused.<br><br>\u201cThere weren\u2019t any geese today,\u201d said Emily.<br><br>\u201cI know.\u201d<br><br>\u201cI\u2019m preparing for next time.\u201d<br><br>The whole group burst into laughter.<br><br>Mrs Patel smiled.<br><br>\u201cThat may be the most peculiar answer I\u2019ve ever heard.\u201d<br><br>As the coach travelled home, Morice looked out of the window. The treasure hunt had been far more than a game. It had taught the pupils to solve problems carefully, trust one another and use technology wisely. Ben quietly opened his chocolate medal.<br><br>\u201cI\u2019ve decided not to plunder anyone else\u2019s biscuits.\u201d<br><br>Emily smiled.<br><br>\u201cThat\u2019s real progress.\u201d<br><br>Ben nodded.<br><br>\u201cBesides\u2026\u201d<br><br>\u201cMy own biscuits taste better anyway.\u201d<br><br>",
