    "story": "The Unorthodox Swimming Gala<br><br>A month before starting Stretford Grammar School, Morice and the other new Year 6 pupils were invited to a friendly swimming gala. It was held in a majestic sports centre with a lofty glass roof that let sunshine pour into the pool. The event was surprisingly lavish, with colourful banners, music and even free fruit for every competitor.<br><br>\u201cIt is a wonderful day,\u201d announced Mrs Hughes. \u201cYou should feel proud to be here.\u201d<br><br>Ben grinned.<br><br>\u201cI already do. Especially because the snacks are free.\u201d<br><br>\u2e3b<br><br>The changing rooms were supervised by Mr Barker, a stern swimming coach. His rules were extremely rigid.<br><br>\u201cNo running.\u201d<br><br>\u201cNo diving unless instructed.\u201d<br><br>\u201cNo splashing people on purpose.\u201d<br><br>Ben whispered to Morice,<br><br>\u201cI think he wrote those rules after meeting me.\u201d<br><br>\u2e3b<br><br>The first race began quietly.<br><br>The crowd became subdued as the swimmers climbed onto the starting blocks.<br><br>Morice stretched carefully while Ben bounced up and down.<br><br>\u201cYou\u2019ll wear yourself out,\u201d Emily warned.<br><br>\u201cI\u2019ve got endless energy.\u201d<br><br>\u201cYou always say that.\u201d<br><br>\u2e3b<br><br>When the whistle blew, Morice dived into the water with nimble movements.<br><br>His smooth strokes looked almost effortless.<br><br>The audience applauded.<br><br>\u201cHis technique is unsurpassed!\u201d one parent exclaimed.<br><br>Ben cheered so loudly that even the lifeguard laughed.<br><br>\u2e3b<br><br>Halfway through the race, one swimmer became tired.<br><br>\u201cI might succumb to fatigue,\u201d he muttered.<br><br>Morice encouraged him.<br><br>\u201cKeep going! You\u2019re nearly there!\u201d<br><br>The swimmer smiled and finished the race.<br><br>\u2e3b<br><br>Afterwards, everyone gathered beside a venerable swimming coach who had trained champions for over forty years.<br><br>He spoke kindly.<br><br>\u201cWinning is wonderful, but being a virtuous teammate is even more important.\u201d<br><br>The pupils nodded.<br><br>\u2e3b<br><br>Ben discovered that only a trifle of cake remained on the refreshment table.<br><br>\u201cThis is terrible!\u201d he sighed dramatically.<br><br>Emily looked into his lunch bag.<br><br>\u201cYou\u2019ve brought three sandwiches, two bananas and four cereal bars.\u201d<br><br>\u201cI like to be prepared.\u201d<br><br>\u201cThat sounds rather superfluous.\u201d<br><br>\u2e3b<br><br>Just then, a small boy accidentally knocked over a bottle of sports drink.<br><br>The liquid spread across the floor.<br><br>The lifeguard hurried over to stop anyone slipping.<br><br>Ben grabbed a mop.<br><br>\u201cI\u2019ll help!\u201d<br><br>Within minutes the area was clean.<br><br>The pupils clapped.<br><br>\u201cYou\u2019ve managed to revive the snack table,\u201d laughed Oliver.<br><br>\u2e3b<br><br>Outside, dark clouds gathered.<br><br>The weather suddenly became **volatile**.<br><br>The wind grew stronger and stronger.<br><br>\u201cThe forecast mentioned tempestuous conditions,\u201d said Mrs Hughes.<br><br>\u201cLet\u2019s move everyone indoors before the weather becomes too turbulent.\u201d<br><br>\u2e3b<br><br>While everyone waited, Ben entertained the younger children with an unorthodox swimming lesson.<br><br>He demonstrated how not to swim by pretending to flap like a penguin.<br><br>The children laughed so hard that one nearly fell off a bench.<br><br>Mrs Hughes smiled.<br><br>\u201cIt isn\u2019t proper technique\u2026\u201d<br><br>\u201c\u2026but it certainly improves everyone\u2019s mood.\u201d<br><br>\u2e3b<br><br>Suddenly two boys began arguing about whose relay team was better.<br><br>Their voices became louder and louder.<br><br>Mrs Hughes quickly stepped between them to stop the disagreement.<br><br>\u201cI think it\u2019s time to quell this argument.\u201d<br><br>The boys immediately became quiet and submissive.<br><br>\u201cWe\u2019re sorry.\u201d<br><br>\u2e3b<br><br>A younger swimmer started crying because he thought he had lost his lucky goggles.<br><br>His face looked absolutely **wretched**.<br><br>\u201cI\u2019ll never swim again!\u201d<br><br>Morice searched beneath a bench and found them.<br><br>\u201cThey were here all along.\u201d<br><br>The boy smiled.<br><br>\u201cYou\u2019ve saved my day!\u201d<br><br>\u2e3b<br><br>Meanwhile, Ben noticed a coach carrying a very stout toolbox.<br><br>\u201cWhat\u2019s inside?\u201d<br><br>\u201cEverything needed to repair swimming equipment,\u201d the coach replied.<br><br>Ben peeked inside.<br><br>\u201cThere are enough tools to build another swimming pool!\u201d<br><br>\u2e3b<br><br>During the relay final, one team tried a little subterfuge.<br><br>They secretly swapped the running order without telling the officials.<br><br>The referee spotted the mistake immediately.<br><br>\u201cI\u2019m afraid you\u2019ll have to use the correct order.\u201d<br><br>The pupils apologised.<br><br>\u2e3b<br><br>After the races, everyone gathered for lunch.<br><br>Morice drank two bottles of water.<br><br>\u201cThat certainly helped quench my thirst.\u201d<br><br>Ben replied,<br><br>\u201cI\u2019ve already quenched mine twice.\u201d<br><br>\u2e3b<br><br>Near the entrance stood an old plant that had begun to **wither** because it had not been watered.<br><br>The caretaker fetched a watering can.<br><br>\u201cI\u2019ll look after it.\u201d<br><br>\u201cPerhaps it\u2019ll recover,\u201d said Morice.<br><br>\u201cIt probably will,\u201d replied the caretaker.<br><br>\u201cPlants are often tougher than they look.\u201d<br><br>\u2e3b<br><br>As the prizes were presented, Mrs Hughes smiled.<br><br>\u201cYou\u2019ve all shown determination, kindness and teamwork.\u201d<br><br>She looked at Ben.<br><br>\u201cAnd you\u2019ve shown us that enthusiasm is useful\u2026\u201d<br><br>\u201c\u2026although sometimes it can become a slight nuisance.\u201d<br><br>Everyone laughed.<br><br>Ben bowed dramatically.<br><br>\u201cI\u2019ll accept that.\u201d<br><br>\u2e3b<br><br>On the coach home, Morice looked out of the window.<br><br>\u201cThe best part wasn\u2019t winning.\u201d<br><br>\u201cIt was helping everyone enjoy the day.\u201d<br><br>Ben nodded.<br><br>\u201cI agree.\u201d<br><br>Then he reached into his bag.<br><br>\u201cWould anyone like the superfluous cereal bars I packed?\u201d<br><br>Emily laughed.<br><br>\u201cSo they finally have a purpose?\u201d<br><br>Ben smiled.<br><br>\u201cYes.\u201d<br><br>\u201cAnd if nobody wants them\u2026\u201d<br><br>\u201c\u2026I definitely won\u2019t let them go to waste.\u201d<br><br>The whole coach burst into laughter, and everyone agreed that the swimming gala had been unforgettable\u2014not just because of the races, but because friendship, kindness and a very over-prepared lunch bag had made it a day to remember.<br><br>",
